[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:nuxt/javascript-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
[src:nuxt/nuxt] The main advantage of Nuxt over using Vue alone is its universal rendering system.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] The framework works as both an in-browser single-page application (SPA) as well as a server-rendered static website, by "hydrating" a server-rendered page to a full SPA after it is loaded.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] This allows websites to have the search engine optimization and performance benefits of a server-rendered site in addition to the interactivity of a client-rendered application.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Nuxt largely abstracts the server-rendering features from the developer, and it's therefore able to have a similar development experience to a traditional SPA using Vue's single-file component (SFC) system.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] In addition to its universal rendering mechanism, Nuxt also provides many other benefits and quality-of-life features, such as path-based routing, hot module replacement (HMR), TypeScript support out of the box, and middleware and server logic.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Rather than a regular Vue.js application, which ordinarily requires every route to be manually registered, Nuxt uses path-based routing to automatically register every route in an application.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Pages are declared in the `pages/` folder, where the name of the page file becomes the name of the route.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Dynamic parameters can be added using square brackets, and catch-all routes can be added using three dots and square brackets, much like JavaScript's array spread syntax.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Nuxt automatically imports most Vue composition API functions, and any helper functions from the `composables/` and `utils/` folders.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Nuxt supports SSR-friendly layouts out of the box, which allows similar pages to use the same basic templates, such as a header and footer.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Layouts are declared in the `layouts/` folder, and work using native Vue slots.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] To enable layouts in a Nuxt project, the entry point of the application, `app.vue`, must include a `NuxtLayout` component to toggle between layouts for each page.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] The default layout is located at `layouts/default.vue`, and must include a slot for the page content.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] A page can use a custom layout by using the `definePageMeta` helper in a setup function or block.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Nuxt adds middleware support to applications, which enables server logic to run between navigation changes.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Both global and page-specific middleware files are supported.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Middleware is declared in the `middleware/` folder, which exports a function that takes in the current and previous routes as parameters.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] From there, globally-available helpers like abortNavigation and navigateTo can be used to control navigation.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Nuxt can also generate server API routes and handlers, using the `server/` folder.
[src:nuxt/nuxt] Any file placed in `server/api` will become an API route, and any file placed in `server/routes` will become a route file, the difference being the final file location (`server/api` adds an api prefix to the path).
[src:nuxt/nuxt] This can now be called from components using the `useFetch` composable.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:nuxt/server-side-rendering] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue.js features an incrementally adaptable architecture that focuses on declarative rendering and component composition.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] The core library is focused on the view layer only.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Advanced features required for complex applications such as routing, state management and build tooling are offered via officially maintained supporting libraries and packages.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue.js allows for extending HTML with HTML attributes called directives.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] The directives offer functionality to HTML applications, and come as either built-in or user defined directives.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue was created by Evan You after working for Google using AngularJS in several projects.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] He later summed up his thought process: "I figured, what if I could just extract the part that I really liked about Angular and build something really lightweight." The first source code commit to the project was dated July 2013, at which time it was originally named "Seed".
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue was first publicly announced the following February, in 2014.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Version names are often derived from manga and anime series, with the first letters arranged in alphabetical order.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] When a new major is released i.e. v3.y.z, the last minor i.e.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] 2.x.y will become a LTS release for 18 months (bug fixes and security patches) and for the following 18 months will be in maintenance mode (security patches only).
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue 3 was officially released in September 2020.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] According to the *State of Vue.js Report 2025*, 96% of surveyed developers reported having used Vue 3.x.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] However, 35% also indicated that they used Vue 2.7.x in the past year, reflecting continued reliance on Vue 2 despite its end of support.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] The report also noted that more than a quarter of respondents encountered challenges when migrating from Vue 2 to Vue 3.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] According to the *State of Vue.js Report 2025*, the Vue's core team recommendation is reflected in developer adoption–over 80% of surveyed developers reported using Pinia while Vuex still had 38.4% usage, indicating ongoing reliance on the older library.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue components extend basic HTML elements to encapsulate reusable code.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] At a high level, components are custom elements to which the Vue's compiler attaches behavior.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] In Vue, a component is essentially a Vue instance with pre-defined options.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] The code snippet below contains an example of a Vue component.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue uses an HTML-based template syntax that allows binding the rendered DOM to the underlying Vue instance's data.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] All Vue templates are valid HTML that can be parsed by specification-compliant browsers and HTML parsers.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue compiles the templates into virtual DOM render functions.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] A virtual Document Object Model (or "DOM") allows Vue to render components in its memory before updating the browser.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Combined with the reactivity system, Vue can calculate the minimal number of components to re-render and apply the minimal amount of DOM manipulations when the app state changes.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue users can use template syntax or choose to directly write render functions using hyperscript either through function calls or JSX.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Render functions allow applications to be built from software components.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue features a reactivity system that uses plain JavaScript objects and optimized re-rendering.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Each component keeps track of its reactive dependencies during its render, so the system knows precisely when to re-render, and which components to re-render.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue provides a variety of ways to apply transition effects when items are inserted, updated, or removed from the DOM.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] If the transition component provided JavaScript hooks, these hooks will be called at appropriate timings.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] If no CSS transitions/animations are detected and no JavaScript hooks are provided, the DOM operations for insertion and/or removal will be executed immediately on next frame.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] A traditional disadvantage of single-page applications (SPAs) is the inability to share links to the exact "sub" page within a specific web page.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Because SPAs serve their users only one URL-based response from the server (it typically serves index.html or index.vue), bookmarking certain screens or sharing links to specific sections is normally difficult if not impossible.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] To solve this problem, many client-side routers delimit their dynamic URLs with a "hashbang" (#!), e.g.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] However, with HTML5 most modern browsers support routing without hashbangs.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue provides an interface to change what is displayed on the page based on the current URL path – regardless of how it was changed (whether by emailed link, refresh, or in-page links).
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Additionally, using a front-end router allows for the intentional transition of the browser path when certain browser events (i.e. clicks) occur on buttons or links.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Vue itself doesn't come with front-end hashed routing.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] But the open-source "vue-router" package provides an API to update the application's URL, supports the back button (navigating history), and email password resets or email verification links with authentication URL parameters.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] It supports mapping nested routes to nested components and offers fine-grained transition control.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] With Vue, developers are already composing applications with small building blocks building larger components.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] With vue-router added to the mix, components must merely be mapped to the routes they belong to, and parent/root routes must indicate where children should render.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Allows the User component to pass in the particular id of the user which was typed into the URL using the $route object's params key: `$route.params.id`.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] This template (varying by the params passed into the router) will be rendered into `<router-view></router-view>` inside the DOM's div#app.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] The core library comes with tools and libraries both developed by the core team and contributors.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Although the Vue.js Ecosystem is generally very well-developed, developers point to some ecosystem gaps as one of the most important thing missing (as of March 2025 Developer Survey in *the State of Vue.js Report 2025*).
[src:nuxt/vue-js] 22% of respondents mentioned the lack of robust, official component libraries like MUI or Radix, and the need for better testing utilities.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] There was also demand for more modular, enterprise-ready solutions for dashboards, e-commerce, and animation libraries similar to Framer Motion.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:nuxt/vue-js] Modern frameworks, such as Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Web performance is the objective measurements and the perceived user experience of load time and runtime.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Web performance is how long a site takes to load, become interactive and responsive, and how smooth the content is during user interactions.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Performance concerns questions like: Is scrolling smooth?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Do pop-ups load quickly and animate fluidly?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The objective measurements include time to load, frames per second, and time to become interactive, and subjective experience means how long it feels like it takes for content to load.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The longer it takes for a site to respond, the more users will abandon the site.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] It is important to minimize the loading and response times and add additional features to conceal latency by making the experience as available and interactive as possible, as soon as possible, while asynchronously loading in the longer tail parts of the experience.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] There are tools, APIs, and best practices that help us measure and improve web performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Performance guides are resources that describe how browsers work, what affects performance, and how to measure, optimize, and monitor performance across various aspects of your application.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In the context of Open Web Apps, this document explains in general what performance is, how the browser platform helps improve it, and what tools and processes you can use to test and improve it.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Users want web experiences with content that is fast to load and smooth to interact with.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Therefore, a developer should strive to achieve these two goals.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] To understand how to improve performance and perceived performance, it helps to understand how the browser works.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] There are no clear set rules as to what constitutes a slow pace when loading pages, but there are specific guidelines for indicating content will load (1 second), idling (50ms), animating (16.7ms) and responding to user input (50 to 200ms).
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Improving your startup performance is often one of the highest value performance optimizations that can be made.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Good user experience includes ensuring your app loads quickly.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article provides performance tips and suggestions for both writing new applications and porting applications to the web from other platforms.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Critical Rendering Path is the sequence of steps the browser goes through to convert the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript into pixels on the screen.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Optimizing the critical render path improves render performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The critical rendering path includes the Document Object Model (DOM), CSS Object Model (CSSOM), render tree and layout.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] A performance budget is a limit to prevent regressions.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] It can apply to a file, a file type, all files loaded on a page, a specific metric (e.g., Time to Interactive), a custom metric (e.g., Time to Hero Element), or a threshold over a period of time.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Animations are critical for a pleasurable user experience on many applications.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] There are many ways to implement web animations, such as CSS `transitions`/`animations` or JavaScript-based animations (using `requestAnimationFrame()`).
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article, we analyze the performance differences between CSS-based and JavaScript-based animation.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Animation on the web can be done via `SVG`, `JavaScript`, including `<canvas>` and `WebGL`, CSS `animation`, `<video>`, animated GIFs and even animated PNGs and other image types.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The performance cost of animating a CSS property can vary from one property to another, and animating expensive CSS properties can result in Jank as the browser struggles to hit a smooth frame rate.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The MDN Web Performance Learning Area contains modern, up-to-date tutorials covering Performance essentials.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article discusses why web performance is important for accessibility, user experience and your business goals.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] You know web performance is important, but what factors affect web performance and how is it measured?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article introduces the components of performance, from web page loading and rendering, including how your content makes it into your users' browser to be viewed, to what groups of people we need to consider when thinking about performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] More important than how fast your website is in milliseconds, is how fast your users perceive your site to be.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] These perceptions are impacted by actual page load time, idling, responsiveness to user interaction, and the smoothness of scrolling and other animations.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article, we discuss the various loading metrics, animation, and responsiveness metrics, along with best practices to improve user perception, if not the actual timings.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Now that you understand a few performance metrics, we take a deeper dive into performance tools, metrics, and APIs and how we can make performance part of the web development workflow.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The lowest hanging fruit of web performance is often media optimization.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Serving different media files based on each user agent's capability, size, and pixel density is possible.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article we discuss the impact images have on performance, and the methods to reduce the number of bytes sent per image.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article we discuss the impact video content has on performance, and cover tips like removing audio tracks from background videos can improve performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] JavaScript, when used properly, can allow for interactive and immersive web experiences — or it can significantly harm download time, render time, in-app performance, battery life, and user experience.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article outlines some JavaScript best practices that should be considered to ensure even complex content is as performant as possible.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Some attributes and the source order of your markup can impact the performance or your website.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] By minimizing the number of DOM nodes, making sure the best order and attributes are used for including content such as styles, scripts, media, and third-party scripts, you can drastically improve the user experience.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article looks in detail at how HTML can be used to ensure maximum performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] CSS may be a less important optimization focus for improved performance, but there are some CSS features that impact performance more than others.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article we look at some CSS properties that impact performance and suggested ways of handling styles to ensure performance is not negatively impacted.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] There are many things a developer can do to improve performance, but how fast is fast enough?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] How can you convince powers that be of the importance of these efforts?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Once optimized, how can you ensure bloat doesn't come back?
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In this article we look at convincing management, developing a performance culture and performance budget, and introduce ways to ensure regressions don't sneak into your code base.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This article covers several topics at a basic level and provides links to deeper dives to improve performance for each topic.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] In addition to front-end topics such as HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and media files, it also covers APIs, developer tools, best practices, and bad practices relating to web performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Performance API is a group of standards used to measure the performance of web applications.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Performance API allows high precision measurements that are based on time in potential sub-millisecond resolution and a stable monotonic clock that is not subject to system clock skew or adjustments.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The high resolution timers are needed for accurate benchmarking instead of the less precise and non-monotonic `Date` timestamps.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming.notRestoredReasons` property reports information on why the current document was blocked from using the bfcache on navigation.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Developers can use this information to identify pages that need updates to make them bfcache-compatible, thereby improving site performance.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Navigation Timing provides metrics associated with navigating from one page to another via the PerformanceNavigationTiming API.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] For example, you can determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document, or log the time it took until DOM construction has finished and interaction with the DOM is possible.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Performance API doesn't provide performance data analysis, or visualizations.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] However, the Performance API is integrated well with developer tools and its data is often sent to analytics end points and libraries to record performance metrics which help you to evaluate the data to find performance bottlenecks affecting your users.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This page provides an overview about what sorts of Performance API data exists, how it is collected, and how it can be accessed.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Resource Timing enables retrieving and analyzing detailed network timing data for the loading of an application's resources.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to load a specific resource (such as an image or a script) either implicitly as part of page load or explicitly from JavaScript, for example using the `fetch()` API.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Server-Timing allows servers to communicate metrics about the request-response cycle to the user agent.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] You can collect this information and act on server-side metrics in the same way as all the other metrics processed with the Performance API.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Create application specific timestamps using the user timing API's "mark" and "measure" entry types using high-precision timestamps that are part of the browser's performance timeline.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Provides events you can watch for to know when a document becomes visible or hidden, as well as features to look at the current visibility state of the page.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The **Cooperative Scheduling of Background Tasks API** (also referred to as the Background Tasks API or the `requestIdleCallback()` API) provides the ability to queue tasks to be executed automatically by the user agent when it determines that there is free time to do so.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Beacon interface schedules an asynchronous and non-blocking request to a web server.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The Intersection Observer API provides a way to asynchronously observe changes in the intersection of a target element with an ancestor element or with a top-level document's Viewport.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This enabled use cases such as Timing element visibility to get asynchronously notified when elements of interest become visible.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Exposes decoding and encoding abilities of a client device, such as whether media is supported and whether playback should be smooth and power efficient, with real time feedback about playback to better enable adaptive streaming, and access to display property information.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Information about the system's connection in terms of general connection type (e.g., 'wifi, 'cellular', etc.).
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This can be used to select high definition content or low definition content based on the user's connection.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The **Battery API**, provides information about the system's battery charge level and lets you be notified by events that are sent when the battery level or charging status change.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This can be used to adjust your app's resource usage to reduce battery drain when the battery is low, or to save changes before the battery runs out in order to prevent data loss.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The **`deviceMemory`** read-only property of the `Navigator` interface returns the approximate amount of device memory in gigabytes.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] The **`preloadResponse`** read-only property of the `FetchEvent` interface returns a `Promise` that resolves to the navigation preload `Response` if navigation preload was triggered, or `undefined` otherwise.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] This website provides information on how to use and understand the performance features in your developer tools, including Call Tree, Flame Graph, Stack Chart, Marker Chart and Network Chart.
[src:nuxt/web-performance] Learn how to profile app performance with Firefox's built-in profiler.
